    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-10T20:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-10T20:23:00-05:00" n="127"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d127">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/23562: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Guaymas</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Yost</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guaymas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-10T18:00:00-07:23">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 10, 1920—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 11—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Sonora State Legislative Assembly last night fully endorsed recent action of the
                    Governor giving him full powers over all State finances and war, until the end
                    of September. Federal Government is not to be repudiated until the Federal
                    troops arrive in Sonora. Telegraphic communication is cut off with Sinaloa also
                    shipments of merchandise. Americans here are quite [omission] it is considered
                    highly desirable that a war vessel be available for Guaymas in case of
                    emergency.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Yost</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
